metadata.name: Fleuve #40
metadata.description:
River at rural,
Burn and glittered, 
Like silver and gold,
Before her eyes the dark thought wood,
Flow with chant and hold of motion,
Flashed wild with a running water,
Gleam for the day of that life and love,
Warm with our morning splendor.
_

Generative visual composition, hybrid techniques, textures source created with GAN, assist by AI, layers transform in autonomous system, eclectic, colors, additional algorithm, modular patch, and combine with other elements that made with code.

metadata.name: Composition #4 #16
metadata.description:
When I'm working on a problem, I never think about beauty. But when I've finished, if the solution is not beautiful... I know it's wrong.
[Buckminster Fuller]

I tried to hybridize, in a schematic way only, the architectural language of neoplasticism with some characteristics of Islamic architecture. The result seems to me to convey a certain elegance...
As with the other "Composition #" series, you can explore the model interactively in 3D space.

metadata.name: CITYBLOCKS: GENESIS #69
metadata.description:
On desktop, open project in live view and click “S” to download STL file (printable / experimental)
Rotate and zoom with the mouse to explore the model

Cityblocks: Genesis

In the Cityblocks series, urban ensembles are generated with a simple click. With each iteration appears a new densely built city block. Graced with impeccable geometrical lines, devoid of any human presence, these buildings remind us of brutalist utopias like Le Corbusier’s Cité radieuse or Niemeyer’s Brasilia. But despite their clearly modernist feel, there is something hauntingly primitive about them. They could be either New Mexican adobe pueblos, Minoan palaces, or Turkish troglodyte dwellings. Both carved and sculpted, these Ghormenghasts of concrete float in a realm out of time, like in some architect’s dream.

The purpose of this creative work is to generate 3D architectural projects that could be implemented in the real world. The accelerating lives that we live, complicated by growing and unpredictable environmental crises, call for an enhanced capacity to come up quickly with new architectural solutions adapted to different contexts. From computer assisted design to 3D printing, from augmented reality to real-life housing, from sculpture to architecture, this work aims at bridging the gap between the virtual and the tangible.

Working as a visual artist, David Umemoto draws inspiration from his training as an architect. He has been using low-tech methods for a long time, refining his talent for elegant simple shapes and combinatory constructions. Now, poured concrete and home-made moulds are giving way to zero-gravity rotating models. The skills he developed while working with real objects find a new playground in the virtual realm.

metadata.name: Stones and Sticks #36
metadata.description:
In this project I explore the technique for creating figures, lights, and shades by only using the line primitive. I imagine a primitive world, a distant planet where life can begin again or has just been swept away by some deadly wind. Stones and sticks the only means for building and creating useful tools, just like in this computer-generated image.
-	Hit ‘s’ to save a hi res (5683x3072) png file
-	Dark, Light and Gold modes

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #106
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: twofiftythousand #344
metadata.description:
twofiftythousand is about the chaos of unlimited decisions. Look for a pattern in the noise.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

metadata.name: Nothing Remains #25
metadata.description:
The only time I ever received corporal punishment – something that was still legal in schools during the 1970s – was in Double Maths with Mrs Robinson. The log book spread out before me seemed less appealing than talking with my friends at the back of the classroom, and so it was I found myself, palm outstretched, feeling the whack of Mrs. Robinson's ruler, ten times over. "Math sucks." Or so I thought.

Back then I knew nothing of the beauty that I would later see in Mathematics – something which became apparent as I taught myself to code, especially using Processing.

This work – based on code I've been playing around with since 2009 – is my small homage to that beauty. Originally based on Ulam spirals, I've then played around with that starting formula to create an infinite numbers of patterns using square roots, cosines and modulus. If only they had shown me these possibilities when I was younger I may have avoided the dreaded ruler of Mrs. Robinson.

metadata.name: Stacked Containers #24
metadata.description:
There is nothing more intriguing than balancing, and balancing things out, when nothing falls through, is a sign that we are thriving and evolving. With this purpose in mind I developed this artwork that balances colors in blocks of various sizes, just like the problems in our lives.

Press S to save as png
August, 2022, Pierre Zamboni

metadata.name: Lost In The Pyramids #17
metadata.description:
This project is a strange story about us getting lost in the pyramids.
Layers seem to be broken as if you are lost in the fifth dimension among many others.
A peculiar illusion that is framed and depicted with different colors.

- Press "S" to save an artwork.
- Press "N" to save without frame.

- Collectors who own this NFT have the right to print the work.
Made with p5js.
